### Cytokine-cytokine receptor interaction

The cytokine-cytokine receptor interaction pathway involves a network of signaling events triggered by the binding of cytokines to their specific receptors on target cells. This interaction is crucial for regulating immune responses, cell growth, and differentiation. In the context of glioblastoma, dysregulation of cytokine signaling can contribute to tumor progression and immune evasion. Tumor cells often exploit cytokine signaling pathways to promote a microenvironment that supports their growth and suppresses effective immune responses.

### IL-17 signaling pathway

The IL-17 signaling pathway is activated by the interleukin-17 (IL-17) family of cytokines, which are involved in inflammatory and autoimmune responses. IL-17 binds to its receptors on various cell types, leading to the activation of signaling cascades that promote inflammation and immune cell recruitment.In cancer, IL-17 can contribute to tumor progression by promoting inflammation and creating an environment that supports tumor growth. Elevated IL-17 levels have been associated with poor prognosis in various cancers, including glioblastoma.

### Viral Protein Interaction with Cytokine and Cytokine Receptor

This pathway involves interactions between viral proteins and host cytokines or their receptors. Such interactions can modulate the host’s immune response, either by evading immune detection or by altering cytokine signaling. The enrichment of this pathway in glioblastoma highlights potential viral influences or mechanisms mimicking viral interactions, which may affect tumor behavior and immune responses.
